Lypoglossa franclemonti

can be distinguished from 

L. angularis

by a less transverse pronotum, more elongate antennal articles; the apex of the median lobe (in parameral view) broadest at the base, not constricted (

Figs. 
64–65

; 
25–27
); no projections at the base of the apex (

Figs. 
64–67

; 
25–29
); a smaller sclerite of the parameres (

Figs. 
69

; 
31
); and the proximal loop of the spermatheca wider, almost circular (

Figs. 
70

; 
32
).

Lypoglossa franclemonti

differs from 

L. manitobae

in having a larger body size; apex of the median lobe (in parameral view) broadest at the base, not constricted (

Figs. 
64–65

; 
55–57
); no projections at the base of the apex (

Figs. 
64–67

; 
55–59
); a smaller sclerite of parameres (

Figs. 
69

; 
61
); and a larger spermatheca (

Figs. 
70

; 
62–63
).

Abdominal terga with very fine (poorly visible at
70 x
) microsculpture consisting of transverse waves; terga 3–5 matte due to fine and dense punctation, distance between punctures equals 1–2 times their diameter, terga 6–7 glossy, with sparser punctation, distance between punctures equals 2–4 times their diameter.
